53
00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:13.840
So first, a bit of review as to why Project Optimus came to

54
00:03:13.900 --> 00:03:16.700
be. There are a few main threads that came together.

55
00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:20.980
The first being that historically, the way that we have chosen the dosages for

56
00:03:21.100 --> 00:03:24.580
cancer drugs is based on something called the maximum tolerated dose,

57
00:03:25.140 --> 00:03:27.600
which was developed for cytotoxic chemotherapies.

58
00:03:28.350 --> 00:03:31.710
Small numbers of patients would be exposed to escalating doses,

59
00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:35.840
evaluated for dose-limiting toxicities, and then eventually the

60
00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:38.530
MTT, or maximum tolerated dose, would be reached.

61
00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:43.040
Only serious or life-threatening toxicities were considered dose-limiting, and the

62
00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:46.280
observation period for these toxicities was quite short.

63
00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:50.950
Of course, most cancer drugs in development today are targeted drugs or

64
00:03:51.060 --> 00:03:54.190
biologics, and they have different properties from cytotoxic

65
00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:57.480
chemotherapies. One being that unlike cytotoxic

66
00:03:57.500 --> 00:03:58.560
chemotherapies, which

67
00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:03.860
may be given for a fixed number of cycles, some of these newer drugs, because

68
00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:07.580
of their efficacy, may be given for many months or even years.

69
00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:11.380
And so low-grade tolerability, things like Grade 1 or 2 diarrhea,

70
00:04:11.780 --> 00:04:15.320
become very, very important to the overall tolerability of the drug.

71
00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:19.250
Additionally, some of these newer drugs have different scientific properties from

72
00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:22.890
cytotoxic chemotherapies, such that a lower dose may have

73
00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:25.880
similar efficacy but better safety to a higher

74
00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:27.420
dose.

75
00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:36.160
Second, many stakeholders, including patients, patient

76
00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:39.120
advocates, oncologists, professional societies,

77
00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:43.220
regulators, and industry, all recognize that the lack

78
00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:47.120
of dosage optimization for cancer drugs was a huge problem with negative

79
00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:50.520
consequences on patient lives. And so this slide

80
00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:54.100
highlights that across stakeholders, there were growing calls to action

81
00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:57.980
for dosage optimization for cancer drugs.

82
00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:03.400
And then finally, FDA also became concerned because in some

83
00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:07.060
cases, lack of dosage optimization might have severe

84
00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:11.060
negative consequences, including potential detrimental impacts on overall

85
00:05:11.070 --> 00:05:14.940
survival. So PI3K kinase inhibitors were approved

86
00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:18.840
for hematologic malignancies on the basis of overall response rate

87
00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:21.420
or progression-free survival data.

88
00:05:21.430 --> 00:05:25.360
And later, in large randomized trials for several of these products, potential

89
00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:28.410
detrimental impacts on overall survival were observed.

90
00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:32.820
When FDA looked at these cases, we realized that one of the contributors

91
00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:36.760
to these potential detrimental impacts on overall survival could be a

92
00:05:36.820 --> 00:05:40.810
lack of dosage optimization early in development, leading to problems with

93
00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:44.250
safety later on at the doses that were selected to be carried forward.

94
00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:51.040
So for all of those reasons, FDA Oncology Center of Excellence established

95
00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:54.960
Project Optimus with the mission of reforming the dosing paradigm in oncology

96
00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:58.880
drug development. And who we are is a multidisciplinary team of

97
00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:02.840
scientists across FDA with expertise in different aspects of

98
00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:05.300
dosage optimization, and there's more information on our

99
00:06:05.340 --> 00:06:08.804
website.The ways in which we implemented

100
00:06:09.944 --> 00:06:13.484
Project Optimus and dosage optimization is through guidance documents,

101
00:06:13.904 --> 00:06:17.864
the oncology dosing toolkit, I'll go into more detail on both of these things on

102
00:06:17.884 --> 00:06:21.674
later slides, and also through milestone meetings and other

103
00:06:21.804 --> 00:06:23.904
formal interactions with drug sponsors.

104
00:06:24.484 --> 00:06:27.724
So now, before even the first in-human clinical trial is

105
00:06:27.964 --> 00:06:31.584
initiated, FDA is providing advice on dosage optimization,

106
00:06:32.024 --> 00:06:35.804
and drug sponsors are seeking our input on dosage optimization throughout

107
00:06:35.864 --> 00:06:36.344
meetings

108
00:06:39.363 --> 00:06:43.004
prior to drug approval, and our advice can become more specific and more tailored

109
00:06:43.044 --> 00:06:45.303
as more information is available on a product.

110
00:06:46.044 --> 00:06:49.824
One thing to highlight, Type D meetings is a new meeting type that was offered

111
00:06:49.884 --> 00:06:52.284
under PDUFA VII. It's more focused.

112
00:06:52.344 --> 00:06:56.174
It has a slightly faster turnaround time, and we've noticed in particular that

113
00:06:56.184 --> 00:06:59.904
drug sponsors are using this type of interaction to seek

114
00:06:59.964 --> 00:07:01.844
feedback on dosage optimization.

115
00:07:04.864 --> 00:07:08.344
So next, I'll go through a little bit of the key principles in the dosage

116
00:07:08.364 --> 00:07:12.284
optimization guidance, which was developed specifically for oncology

117
00:07:12.304 --> 00:07:12.763
drugs.

118
00:07:13.784 --> 00:07:17.004
So ideally, dosage optimization should occur prior to drug

119
00:07:17.064 --> 00:07:20.724
approval, and rather than focusing on one aspect like

120
00:07:20.824 --> 00:07:24.764
safety or DLTs, it's very important to use the totality

121
00:07:24.804 --> 00:07:28.264
of information available to guide dosage selection, which

122
00:07:28.304 --> 00:07:31.504
includes PK/PD data, safety, early

123
00:07:31.644 --> 00:07:35.164
efficacy, and especially dose and exposure response relationship

124
00:07:35.264 --> 00:07:36.014
information.

125
00:07:37.084 --> 00:07:40.764
I'll go into more detail on the next slide and highlight how randomized comparisons

126
00:07:40.844 --> 00:07:43.624
can support identification of optimized dosages.

127
00:07:44.344 --> 00:07:47.844
As I alluded to earlier, safety assessments should include

128
00:07:48.464 --> 00:07:52.424
things like low-grade symptomatic toxicities, which can be very problematic,

129
00:07:52.744 --> 00:07:56.604
affecting tolerability. And then finally, there is

130
00:07:56.644 --> 00:08:00.524
no one size fits all. It's important that the dosage optimization strategy

131
00:08:00.664 --> 00:08:04.424
be appropriate for the specific drug and the specific disease in

132
00:08:04.464 --> 00:08:08.184
which the drug is being developed, and FDA can provide advice.

133
00:08:11.184 --> 00:08:15.024
So this slide highlights pictorially some of the key aspects of the

134
00:08:15.044 --> 00:08:18.604
dosage optimization guidance, and this is what an updated dosage

135
00:08:18.644 --> 00:08:22.064
selection strategy could look like, implementing the principles of dosage

136
00:08:22.144 --> 00:08:25.964
optimization. So during dose escalation, rather than have the

137
00:08:25.984 --> 00:08:29.784
goal of identifying the maximum tolerated dose, instead, the goal could

138
00:08:29.864 --> 00:08:32.924
be to identify a potentially therapeutic dose range.

139
00:08:33.605 --> 00:08:37.225
After this, several dosages within that dose range could be

140
00:08:37.284 --> 00:08:40.424
compared in a randomized assessment for more dosage

141
00:08:40.504 --> 00:08:44.344
optimization. I want to emphasize that the point of this randomized

142
00:08:44.364 --> 00:08:48.204
comparison is not to prove that one dose is statistically superior

143
00:08:48.264 --> 00:08:52.114
to another. Instead, the purpose of randomization is really to

144
00:08:52.144 --> 00:08:55.754
try and have some balance in the baseline characteristics of the patients being

145
00:08:55.784 --> 00:08:59.464
evaluated to have easier interpretation of the dose response

146
00:08:59.484 --> 00:09:03.244
relationships. After that, rather than the maximum tolerated

147
00:09:03.324 --> 00:09:07.154
dose, an optimized dosage could be evaluated in a randomized controlled

148
00:09:07.244 --> 00:09:09.264
trial with a standard of care control arm.

149
00:09:10.024 --> 00:09:14.013
And if that optimized dosage succeeds, then that would become the recommended

150
00:09:14.064 --> 00:09:15.544
dosage in FDA labeling.

151
00:09:16.484 --> 00:09:20.384
The arrows on the slide illustrate that dosage optimization does not need to

152
00:09:20.464 --> 00:09:23.564
occur as a standalone, separate clinical trial.

153
00:09:23.924 --> 00:09:27.224
This is something that, depending on the development program, could be part of a

154
00:09:27.264 --> 00:09:29.304
Phase 1 dosage expansion cohort.

155
00:09:30.184 --> 00:09:34.044
Instead, also, a randomized trial with a standard of care control

156
00:09:34.084 --> 00:09:36.024
arm could have multiple dosage arms.

157
00:09:38.484 --> 00:09:42.324
And then finally, I'll just briefly mention that one other resource that FDA has

158
00:09:42.364 --> 00:09:45.944
available is the Oncology Dosing Toolkit, which was developed to help drug

159
00:09:46.064 --> 00:09:47.494
sponsors and other stakeholders

160
00:09:48.404 --> 00:09:52.324
make informed decisions about which dosages to evaluate in clinical development.

161
00:09:52.834 --> 00:09:56.604
This dosing toolkit highlights key areas that can form the

162
00:09:56.664 --> 00:10:00.564
totality of data that you can use to decide which dosages

163
00:10:00.604 --> 00:10:03.424
to evaluate at different times in clinical development.

164
00:10:07.624 --> 00:10:11.544
So now I want to turn our attention to what has happened,

165
00:10:11.584 --> 00:10:13.584
what has changed over the past five years.

166
00:10:14.224 --> 00:10:18.204
So since initiation of Project Optimus, for most products, FDA is

167
00:10:18.244 --> 00:10:22.164
providing dosage optimization advice before the first in-human trial

168
00:10:22.224 --> 00:10:25.904
is initiated, as early as pre-IND meetings or during an initial

169
00:10:26.084 --> 00:10:30.044
30-day IND submission. In many programs, we've noticed

170
00:10:30.084 --> 00:10:33.784
that drug sponsors are incorporating backfill, additional dosage cohorts, and

171
00:10:33.864 --> 00:10:37.534
randomized dosage evaluations in their pre-approval

172
00:10:37.604 --> 00:10:41.284
development program. And on the next slide, I will highlight some case

173
00:10:41.324 --> 00:10:45.304
examples that illustrate that dosage optimization is feasible even for

174
00:10:45.364 --> 00:10:48.904
expedited development programs and how it can improve safety for

175
00:10:48.944 --> 00:10:50.284
patients.

176
00:10:52.524 --> 00:10:56.064
So this slide highlights some recent examples of dosage optimization in

177
00:10:56.124 --> 00:10:59.744
advanced lung cancer. These are all drugs that received their

178
00:10:59.804 --> 00:11:03.034
initial approval for the lung cancer indication shown between

179
00:11:03.164 --> 00:11:06.944
2022 and 2025, so over the time period

180
00:11:07.004 --> 00:11:08.994
under which Project Optimus has occurred.

181
00:11:09.844 --> 00:11:13.024
I'll highlight some things on this slide as you're taking a look.

182
00:11:13.144 --> 00:11:16.964
So the name of the drug is in the left column, and this

183
00:11:17.024 --> 00:11:20.644
includes an antibody drug conjugate, a bispecific T cell

184
00:11:20.704 --> 00:11:24.384
engager, and small molecule kinase inhibitors, indicating that

185
00:11:24.404 --> 00:11:27.784
dosage optimization is feasible for different classes of product.

186
00:11:28.564 --> 00:11:32.474
In the center column, these products all incorporated a randomized

187
00:11:32.544 --> 00:11:36.204
assessment of multiple dosages as part of their pre-approval

188
00:11:36.244 --> 00:11:40.114
development program, and you can see the dosages that were evaluated in that

189
00:11:40.324 --> 00:11:43.504
center column. The column to the right of that,

190
00:11:44.524 --> 00:11:48.384
yes, your right and my right. The column to the right of that shows the dose that

191
00:11:48.424 --> 00:11:51.544
became the recommended dosage in FDA labeling.

192
00:11:51.904 --> 00:11:55.624
And for all four of these cases, actually, the lower dose or the dosing

193
00:11:55.684 --> 00:11:59.244
regimen with the lower doses became the recommended dosage.

194
00:11:59.324 --> 00:12:02.564
So really illustrating that without this dosage optimization,

195
00:12:03.124 --> 00:12:06.564
maybe the higher dose would have been the one that if the program had

196
00:12:06.604 --> 00:12:10.224
succeeded, maybe that would have been the one that would have been the one patients

197
00:12:10.244 --> 00:12:14.224
were exposed to. And really by doing this dosage optimization, the benefit risk

198
00:12:14.264 --> 00:12:16.704
to patients improved for these drugs.

199
00:12:16.764 --> 00:12:20.384
And also, patients are able to receive a safer dose at

200
00:12:20.444 --> 00:12:24.300
theat the time of drug approval. And

201
00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:28.080
then finally, all of these products received accelerated approval for

202
00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:32.300
their initial approval for the lung cancer indication shown, highlighting

203
00:12:32.310 --> 00:12:35.900
that even for these programs on rapid development timelines, dosage

204
00:12:35.980 --> 00:12:39.640
optimization was feasible. And I'm happy to expand

205
00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:43.410
more on the relationship between dosage optimization and

206
00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:46.520
accelerated approval during the Q&amp;A or discussion.

207
00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:53.440
So of course, even with these initial successes, there are continued challenges for

208
00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:57.460
dosage optimization, and these include making sure that the dosage

209
00:12:57.540 --> 00:13:01.060
optimization approach is appropriate to the specific drug and

210
00:13:01.130 --> 00:13:04.940
program rather than something that's a one size

211
00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:05.590
fits all.

212
00:13:06.540 --> 00:13:10.380
Some of the other continued challenges are for randomized evaluations determining

213
00:13:10.389 --> 00:13:11.560
the size of the dosage

214
00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:16.300
cohorts, and then how to best select the dosages to compare to

215
00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:20.370
one another. Best approaches for combination therapies is another

216
00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:24.190
important area of dosage optimization that needs some more attention.

217
00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:28.420
And then finally, how to assess tolerability in early

218
00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:31.920
clinical development in more patient-centric ways and beyond

219
00:13:32.180 --> 00:13:34.280
clinician-assessed reports of safety.

220
00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:39.330
Several of my colleagues on the panel will talk a little bit more, I think, about

221
00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:42.900
all of these points on the bottom of the slide in their talks.

222
00:13:45.140 --> 00:13:48.600
And finally, to conclude, since initiation of Project

223
00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:52.440
Optimus, FDA is providing advice on dosage optimization early in

224
00:13:52.520 --> 00:13:55.840
clinical development, and drug sponsors are conducting dosage

225
00:13:55.920 --> 00:13:58.660
optimization as part of their pre-market development.

226
00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:03.360
The case examples I shared showed that dosage optimization is feasible

227
00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:06.840
even for programs with rapid development timelines and improved

228
00:14:06.920 --> 00:14:10.020
safety and overall benefit risk for patients.

229
00:14:10.890 --> 00:14:14.300
And then finally, I want to highlight that the success

230
00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:17.420
of dosage optimization and the adoption across

231
00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:21.420
oncology is really a testament to all stakeholders,

232
00:14:21.560 --> 00:14:25.320
patients, patient advocates, oncologists, professional societies,

233
00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:29.280
industry regulators, all have understood the importance

234
00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:32.580
of this, and this is really why I think this has been so

235
00:14:32.680 --> 00:14:35.380
successfully taken on over the past few years.

236
00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:39.840
Of course, as my previous slide alluded to, there is still some

237
00:14:39.900 --> 00:14:43.380
important areas where there could be improvement, areas of opportunity for

238
00:14:43.420 --> 00:14:45.400
improvement in dosage optimization.

239
00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:47.040
And

240
00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:52.810
finally, I'd like to thank all of my colleagues at FDA, especially Dr.

241
00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:56.800
Atiq Rahman, my co-lead for Project Optimus, all members of the

242
00:14:56.960 --> 00:14:57.760
FDA team,

243
00:14:58.820 --> 00:15:02.729
and all of you for your attention today, and I'm looking forward to the discussion.

244
00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:11.220
Thank you, Dr. Shaw.

245
00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:16.010
Next we have Dr. Alexia Iossifidis from

246
00:15:16.020 --> 00:15:19.380
Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, talking about

247
00:15:19.420 --> 00:15:23.340
utilizing randomization backfill and expansion cohorts to gain greater

