Then we obtain outcomes from these patients, right? And then we wait.

495
00:30:31.780 --> 00:30:35.680
What's going to happen? The outcomes that we have been using is DLT,

496
00:30:35.760 --> 00:30:39.260
which is dose-limiting toxicity, which are defined based on the National

497
00:30:39.460 --> 00:30:43.339
Cancer Institute Common Terminology Criteria of Adverse Event, the NCI

498
00:30:43.360 --> 00:30:47.160
CTCAE. And we have been using the presence of a Grade 3 or

499
00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:50.330
higher hematologic or Grade 3 or higher non-hematologic toxicity.

500
00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:54.280
And these you can say that are based mainly on safety.

501
00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:58.070
We don't want to see any events that are going to be alarming or life-threatening.

502
00:30:58.970 --> 00:31:02.120
And based on these outcomes, we assign the next cohort of patients.

503
00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:05.660
What we can do here is we can use different designs to decide how we're going to

504
00:31:05.670 --> 00:31:09.120
assign the doses. We can assign doses based on the 3+3, which

505
00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:11.540
that's all history already, hopefully.

506
00:31:11.600 --> 00:31:15.400
We can use the continual reassessment method, the Bayesian optimal interval

507
00:31:15.460 --> 00:31:19.220
designs. All of these are methods that will tell us how to treat the next cohort.

508
00:31:20.350 --> 00:31:24.160
There are differences among them in the case that we're using data only on

509
00:31:24.200 --> 00:31:27.940
the cohort that we have or data across those

510
00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:28.340
levels.

511
00:31:29.140 --> 00:31:32.480
And then we repeat this process until some stopping rule in terms of

512
00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:35.720
sample size or other stopping criteria.

513
00:31:36.200 --> 00:31:39.380
And at the end, we recommend what we think is the tolerable dose.

514
00:31:39.760 --> 00:31:42.920
That in the past has been the maximum tolerated dose that we're

515
00:31:43.020 --> 00:31:46.880
questioning right now. And the MTD has been defined as the

516
00:31:46.900 --> 00:31:49.380
dose that satisfied that originally stated threshold.

517
00:31:50.340 --> 00:31:53.840
The question that comes to mind now is does DLT as defined capture

518
00:31:53.860 --> 00:31:57.180
tolerability, right? It doesn't include information on

519
00:31:57.200 --> 00:32:00.660
those Grade 2 toxicity. So a patient that

520
00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:04.620
experiences a very long, miserable Grade 2 toxicity

521
00:32:04.660 --> 00:32:08.400
would not be considered a DLT, and that in itself could be not well

522
00:32:08.420 --> 00:32:08.940
tolerated.

523
00:32:09.880 --> 00:32:11.620
So how can we address that?

524
00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:16.350
Going back to the FDA dose optimization guideline from 2024, there are a

525
00:32:16.380 --> 00:32:20.240
few statements that mention that the dose that was recommended

526
00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:24.540
may be unnecessarily high, poorly, or not adequately tolerated from the

527
00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:28.180
patient perspective, and that can affect the patient's ability to remain on the

528
00:32:28.200 --> 00:32:32.170
drug. At the same time, one suggestion has been to incorporate

529
00:32:32.240 --> 00:32:36.060
patient-reported outcomes to see if we can enhance the tolerability in

530
00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:39.620
those finding clinical trials, but not just those finding, but subsequent trials as

531
00:32:39.660 --> 00:32:39.820
well.

532
00:32:41.420 --> 00:32:45.260
So why PROs? So I have a little cartoon here to express

533
00:32:45.320 --> 00:32:49.180
that. So when we collect the patient reported outcome, the patient may be

534
00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:50.300
feeling not so great.

535
00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:55.740
This face can say it all. However, when you go to the clinician and they

536
00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:59.640
are writing down the CTCAE, the clinician may think that that's a mild

537
00:32:59.660 --> 00:33:03.580
toxicity and not really a cause for concern, and they write down a

538
00:33:03.640 --> 00:33:05.120
Grade 1 or Grade 2 toxicity.

539
00:33:06.040 --> 00:33:09.240
That, of course, would not constitute a dose-limiting toxicity based on the

540
00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:10.270
definition that we had.

541
00:33:11.440 --> 00:33:14.840
There's a lot of work showing that understanding tolerability

542
00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:18.920
should come directly from the patient, and the PRO is probably better

543
00:33:18.960 --> 00:33:22.440
informed tolerability, right? The patient is speaking directly.

544
00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:26.540
You're collecting the symptom information directly from the patient to say how

545
00:33:26.580 --> 00:33:29.469
well they feel about the symptoms that they're experiencing.

546
00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:33.940
And there's literature to suggest that there's underreporting of symptoms by

547
00:33:33.960 --> 00:33:37.870
clinicians. So sometimes, especially in the phase one setting, it can be that

548
00:33:37.900 --> 00:33:41.430
clinicians will prompt patients for toxicities that they're expecting,

549
00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:45.790
and those are the ones that get captured and not necessarily other symptoms.

550
00:33:47.560 --> 00:33:50.580
So how has been PRO used in the dose finding setting?

551
00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:51.700
We know

552
00:33:52.740 --> 00:33:56.720
there's been surveys, international stakeholders that say 100%

553
00:33:56.780 --> 00:33:59.870
agree that PROs should be used to inform those escalation and those

554
00:34:00.580 --> 00:34:04.380
decisions. And there's an increasing number of clinical trials using

555
00:34:04.940 --> 00:34:08.821
collecting PROs. However, most of these trials don't include clear PRO

556
00:34:08.861 --> 00:34:11.861
objectives of how the PRO is going to be used to inform the

557
00:34:11.900 --> 00:34:15.500
decisions. And there's a lack of consistency on the instruments that are being

558
00:34:15.620 --> 00:34:19.460
used, either a quality of life instrument sometimes, and sometimes they're

559
00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:23.301
most based on symptoms, which they're different in nature.

560
00:34:25.080 --> 00:34:28.611
So what are some considerations before I go into the methods that we can use for

561
00:34:28.680 --> 00:34:32.660
PRO in the dose finding setting? What are general considerations that you should

562
00:34:32.700 --> 00:34:34.200
have when you're including PRO?

563
00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:37.281
Please make sure to use a validated instrument.

564
00:34:37.841 --> 00:34:41.781
Make sure that it is an instrument that is assessing the patient-reported adverse

565
00:34:41.841 --> 00:34:44.240
event, not necessarily quality of life.

566
00:34:44.841 --> 00:34:48.719
So the instrument that has been used more in the phase one setting

567
00:34:48.960 --> 00:34:52.640
is the PRO CTCAE. It is a companion instrument for the

568
00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:57.360
CTCAE that is directly collecting patient-reported information

569
00:34:57.640 --> 00:35:00.700
and focusing on the symptoms that are on the CTCAE.

570
00:35:01.330 --> 00:35:04.380
And it uses a similar grading from

571
00:35:05.480 --> 00:35:09.460
mild, moderate, severe, and Grade 4, which would be

572
00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:10.050
life-threatening.

573
00:35:11.420 --> 00:35:15.060
Evaluate the time commitment from patients to reduce missing data.

574
00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:19.080
It can be quite extensive, especially when the PRO

575
00:35:19.120 --> 00:35:19.610
instruments,

576
00:35:20.440 --> 00:35:24.280
if you have any information about the toxicity of the drug, you could limit

577
00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:27.360
it to the toxicities that you're expecting.

578
00:35:27.380 --> 00:35:30.740
However, in some settings, you might have to ask about everything because you don't

579
00:35:30.750 --> 00:35:33.380
know what the toxicities are going to be.

580
00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:37.300
Include patient advocates to assess the time commitment from the

581
00:35:37.320 --> 00:35:41.080
patients to know that it is doable, and

582
00:35:41.160 --> 00:35:44.220
specify how tolerability will be defined based on these

583
00:35:44.240 --> 00:35:48.200
PROs. We have the dose-limiting toxicities that we have been using from the

584
00:35:48.220 --> 00:35:52.080
CTCAE. However, when we're coming to the PRO CTCAE, how do

585
00:35:52.160 --> 00:35:56.050
we define tolerability? We're going to be having a laundry list of

586
00:35:56.060 --> 00:36:00.010
toxicities and symptoms, and how do we define from there what is tolerable and

587
00:36:00.020 --> 00:36:03.310
what is not? And this is where your patient advocate may really help

588
00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:07.300
you. Also specify how PROs will be used

589
00:36:07.340 --> 00:36:10.460
to inform the dose escalation and dose recommendation decisions.

590
00:36:10.950 --> 00:36:14.820
And in context of what Mira presented, I'm focusing here more on the dose

591
00:36:14.920 --> 00:36:16.040
escalation component,

592
00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:20.790
that first part of the dose optimization framework,

593
00:36:21.520 --> 00:36:24.860
to figure out which doses you should take on to the dose

594
00:36:24.880 --> 00:36:27.140
randomization stage to ensure that they are

595
00:36:27.180 --> 00:36:30.996
tolerable.So what are the approaches that we can use?

596
00:36:31.576 --> 00:36:35.256
The first one, I'm going to go into more detail on each one of them, but the first

597
00:36:35.336 --> 00:36:39.216
idea is to review the PRO that you collect and see how that informs

598
00:36:39.236 --> 00:36:41.576
your CTCAE grading. So that's one approach.

599
00:36:42.136 --> 00:36:46.036
The second approach is more to formally incorporate PRO data by

600
00:36:46.076 --> 00:36:50.016
setting specific thresholds similar to what we do for the DLT

601
00:36:50.036 --> 00:36:52.236
using the CTCAE. What level of

602
00:36:53.736 --> 00:36:56.726
rate of toxicity would be acceptable in that

603
00:36:56.756 --> 00:37:00.116
context? And we can include PRO data for dose

604
00:37:00.176 --> 00:37:03.976
escalation decisions, plus dose estimation, or only

605
00:37:04.096 --> 00:37:07.936
use PRO data at the end of the trial to ensure that the doses that

606
00:37:07.996 --> 00:37:11.936
we take on can be well-tolerated in the dose optimization

607
00:37:12.036 --> 00:37:12.336
stage.

608
00:37:14.016 --> 00:37:17.876
So in the first context for the review of PRO to inform CTCAE grading,

609
00:37:18.296 --> 00:37:20.816
you can see that the general framework is similar here.

610
00:37:21.276 --> 00:37:24.936
The only thing I've added is this PRO CTCAE collection.

611
00:37:25.416 --> 00:37:29.356
So at the same time that we collect the CTCAE data, we can collect

612
00:37:29.396 --> 00:37:33.316
the PRO CTCAE directly from the patient at each of the visits in

613
00:37:33.356 --> 00:37:37.316
which we collect the CTCAE. And that information, in the

614
00:37:37.356 --> 00:37:41.216
logistical sense, can be shared with the clinician to see how that affects

615
00:37:41.226 --> 00:37:41.356
the

616
00:37:42.476 --> 00:37:45.896
grading of the clinician just by knowing what the patient themselves are

617
00:37:45.936 --> 00:37:49.076
feeling. And that's one approach that we can do.

618
00:37:49.896 --> 00:37:53.136
The advantage and disadvantages of that is that

619
00:37:53.196 --> 00:37:56.536
the cons for that is that the PRO is incorporated directly.

